function 
=======
Takes 1 input, returns 1 output
Used for data transformation.

list.stream()
    .map(x -> x * 2);
map() internally uses Function.


public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        
        Function<String, String> function = s->s.toUpperCase();
        Function<String, String> function1 = s->s.substring(0,3);
        Function<String, String> mergeFunction = function.andThen(function1);
        System.out.println(mergeFunction.apply("wasif"));

        Function<Integer,Integer> function2 = x->2*x;
        Function<Integer,Integer> function3 = x->x*x*x;
        
        System.out.println(function2.andThen(function3).apply(2));// 64
        System.out.println(function3.andThen(function2).apply(2));// 16
        System.out.println(function2.compose(function3).apply(2));// 16

        Function<String,String> identityfunction = Function.identity();
        // identity function takes any input gives back any output
        System.out.println(identityfunction.apply("wasif"));

    }
}
BiFunction
============
It takes 2 inputs and returns 1 output.
“BiFunction is used when we want to process two inputs and return a single result.”

public class BiFunctions {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BiFunction<String,String,Integer> biFunction = (x,y)->x.length()+y.length();
        System.out.println(biFunction.apply("Hi","Hello"));
    }
}

